      <div class="meta-divider"></div>
      <div class="meta-item"><span class="meta-label">Also called</span><span class="meta-value">NAP Audit</span></div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>citation audit</strong> is the systematic process of finding and reviewing every online mention of a business's NAP (name, address, phone number) across directories, data aggregators, and review sites. It identifies duplicates, wrong addresses, outdated phone numbers, and missing directory listings that suppress local pack rankings and misdirect customers.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Scope</div>
            <div class="tms-value">40–80 directories</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Recommended cadence</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Every 6 months</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Trust impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">80% of buyers</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">If you have never audited your citations, assume they are wrong. Old addresses, outdated phone numbers, and duplicate Google listings are the default state after any relocation, rebrand, or franchisee change — and Google reads every mismatch as a reason to distrust your listing.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a citation audit?</h2>
        <p>A citation audit is a health check for your local citation profile. It catalogs every place your business is mentioned online — structured directories like Yelp and Bing Places, industry directories, review sites, and the four US data aggregators — then compares each listing against a canonical NAP record.</p>
        <p>Typical audit outputs:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Inconsistency log</strong> — every listing where the name, address, or phone diverges from canonical</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate list</strong> — multiple GBP or Yelp profiles pointing at the same location</li>
          <li><strong>Coverage gap</strong> — high-authority directories where the business is absent</li>
          <li><strong>Aggregator status</strong> — what Data Axle, Neustar, Foursquare, and Factual are pushing downstream</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Why buyers care</div>
          <p>BrightLocal consumer research found that <strong>80% of consumers lose trust in a local business</strong> when they encounter incorrect contact information online. A citation audit is what stops that trust leak.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why citation audits matter for local SEO</h2>
        <p>Skip the audit and every other local SEO tactic gets weaker. Four reasons the audit comes first:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Error discovery.</strong> Most citation problems are invisible from the inside — you never see the outdated Yellowpages entry because you don't search for yourself. An audit surfaces the errors your customers are hitting.</li>
          <li><strong>Duplicate detection.</strong> Duplicate GBP listings split reviews and ranking signals between two profiles that should be one. A pizza franchise we audited had 4 duplicate profiles splitting 180 reviews across 45 total.</li>
          <li><strong>Baseline for measurement.</strong> Without a snapshot of your citation profile today, you can't prove ranking lifts from cleanup work later.</li>
          <li><strong>Competitive benchmarking.</strong> The audit tools that scan your citations also scan competitors — showing you which directories they appear on that you don't.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How a citation audit works</h2>
        <p>Two paths: manual or automated. Most agencies do both — automated for coverage, manual for the high-value listings.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Manual audit flow</span><br>
          Step 1: <span class="uf-label">Document canonical NAP</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> the exact version on your GBP<br>
          Step 2: <span class="uf-label">Search brand name on Google</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> collect top 30 directory hits<br>
          Step 3: <span class="uf-label">Check each listing</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> flag any name, address, or phone drift<br>
          Step 4: <span class="uf-label">Search phone + address</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> catch listings where the name is wrong<br>
          Step 5: <span class="uf-label">Log gaps + duplicates</span> <span class="uf-arrow">→</span> feed into cleanup workflow
        </div>

        <h3>Automated audit tools</h3>
        <p>Tools like <strong>BrightLocal</strong>, <strong>Whitespark</strong>, <strong>Moz Local</strong>, and <strong>Semrush Listing Management</strong> scan 40–80+ directories against your canonical NAP and produce a formatted report. They catch the long tail that manual searches miss — obscure industry directories, city-specific chambers, and legacy aggregators that still show old data.</p>

        <h3>What to look for</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>Wrong physical addresses (post-relocation)</li>
          <li>Old phone numbers still auto-populating from aggregators</li>
          <li>Business name variations (LLC vs no suffix, "and" vs "&amp;")</li>
          <li>Missing high-authority directories in your industry</li>
          <li>Duplicate listings from franchisees, ex-employees, or scrapers</li>
          <li>Missing or incorrect website URLs</li>
          <li>Closed locations that still appear as active</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="types">Manual vs automated citation audit</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
          <table>
            <thead>
              <tr><th>Approach</th><th>Time</th><th>Coverage</th><th>Best for</th></tr>
            </thead>
            <tbody>
              <tr class="row-highlight">
                <td><strong>Automated tool</strong></td>
                <td>Under 10 minutes</td>
                <td class="cell-yes">40–80 directories, benchmarking</td>
                <td>Recurring audits, multi-location brands</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Manual search</strong></td><td>2–4 hours</td><td class="cell-meh">Top 30 directories</td><td>Single-location owner-run businesses</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Hybrid</strong></td><td>3–5 hours</td><td class="cell-yes">Full coverage + high-value review</td><td>Agencies auditing before cleanup</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Aggregator check only</strong></td><td>30 minutes</td><td class="cell-no">4 aggregators, no directories</td><td>Diagnosing why old data keeps returning</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real citation audit examples</h2>
        <p>Two audits we ran that flipped rankings inside 60 days.</p>

        <h3>1. Relocated law firm</h3>
        <p>A firm relocated 18 months before the audit. It surfaced 35 outdated directory listings still showing the old suite number. After corrections, the firm's local pack position for its money keyword lifted 3 spots inside 60 days — no other change to the site.</p>

        <h3>2. Pizza franchise with duplicates</h3>
        <p>The audit found 4 duplicate Google Business Profile listings splitting 180 reviews across 45 total (the largest profile only had 65 reviews). After merging the duplicates into the primary profile, the consolidated listing carried the full 180-review count and moved from position 4 to position 1 in the local pack.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Citation audit vs citation cleanup — what's the difference?</h2>
        <p>An audit finds problems. A cleanup fixes them. Confusing the two is why most local SEO retainers stall.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>A citation audit</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Read-only — nothing changes yet</li>
              <li>Produces a list of discrepancies</li>
              <li>Takes hours (manual) or minutes (tool)</li>
              <li>Should run every 6 months</li>
              <li>Also called a NAP audit</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>A citation cleanup</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Write actions — updates, merges, deletions</li>
              <li>Uses the audit output as its worklist</li>
              <li>Takes 2–3 months to fully propagate</li>
              <li>Runs once, then only after NAP changes</li>
              <li>Also called citation correction</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for a citation audit</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lock canonical NAP before you start.</strong> Copy the exact name, address, and phone from your Google Business Profile. That is your source of truth for the whole audit.</li>
          <li><strong>Search by phone and address, not just brand name.</strong> Brand searches miss listings where the name is misspelled or abbreviated.</li>
          <li><strong>Include the four US data aggregators.</strong> Data Axle, Neustar Localeze, Foursquare, and Factual push data to hundreds of downstream directories — a wrong record here reappears every time.</li>
          <li><strong>Screenshot everything.</strong> When you request a correction from a directory, some ask for proof of the current entry. Screenshots save you a re-audit.</li>
          <li><strong>Score by directory authority.</strong> A wrong entry on Yelp hurts you more than a wrong entry on a niche city chamber page. Prioritize accordingly.</li>
          <li><strong>Run competitor audits at the same time.</strong> Same tool, same run — you get a citation gap list for free.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — auditing once and never again</div>
          <p>Aggregators re-push old data. Franchisees create new listings. Yelp merges profiles automatically. A one-time audit decays within 6 months. Book the next audit into the calendar the day you close the current one.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common citation audit mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Auditing only the top 10 directories</strong> — misses the long tail where aggregator errors hide</li>
          <li><strong>No canonical NAP document</strong> — you cannot audit for consistency without a source of truth</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring closed or moved locations</strong> — old listings still redirect customers away from you</li>
          <li><strong>Only searching brand name</strong> — misses misspelled listings and franchisee typos</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping duplicates check</strong> — the highest-impact finding gets missed entirely</li>
          <li><strong>Auditing but never cleaning up</strong> — the audit is worthless if the fixes never ship</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should I audit citations?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Run a full citation audit every 6 months and immediately after any NAP change — new address, new phone number, or a rebrand. Between audits, use an automated monitoring tool to flag drift in real time.</p></div></div>
          </div>
